I understand there's a problem when trying to create a generic version of this code:

  package Some::Namespace::*::*;
  sub foo {
  }

But that is not unique to Perl. It's actually a general problem of "higher-order functions" that cannot return functions.

Consider a similar situation in C++, which supports generics:

  template <typename T>
  inline T identity(T x) {
    return x;
  }

If we actually wanted this to be an identity function that always returns the input, we have the same problem! We want something like...

  template <typename T>
  typename T::* identity(T x) {
    return x;
  }

...but C++ does not have higher-order types, so this is not possible. The best you can do in C++ is:

  template <typename T>
  typename T::* identity(T x) {
    return &x;
  }

